<article>
    <h1>Air&#xAD;craft din&#xAD;ing</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200927/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-27"><time>2020-09-27</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Take off on a flight of reverie as you en­joy pretty in-flight meals at Sushi Air­ways in Bagh­dad Street.</p>
    <p>The restau­rant is de­signed like a Dou­glas DC-3, an iconic air­liner in the 1930s and 1940s.</p>
    <p>Your flight of fancy be­gins from the first-floor stair­way en­trance, as two mon­i­tors play footage shot from the cock­pit of a plane in flight.</p>
    <p>A sign of the restau­rant’s open­ing hours on the door re­sem­bles a flight in­for­ma­tion dis­play sys­tem.</p>
    <p>Open the door with the handle – de­signed to re­sem­ble the DC-3 pi­lot’s steer­ing wheel – and you will see a floor mat with run­way thresh­old mark­ings.</p>
    <p>Go up the metal stair­case – meant to repli­cate air­craft board­ing stairs – and a lead­ing stew­ardess wel­comes you on board Sushi Air­ways.</p>
    <p>The long, nar­row din­ing area has air­craft cabin light­ing and feels a tad en­closed, just like on a plane. The restau­rant now seats 20 for safe dis­tanc­ing, down from 27.</p>
    <p>Its con­cept stems from 61-yearold owner Arul In­thi­rara­jah’s love for the DC-3. In 1966, his fam­ily was evac­u­ated from Kota Baru in the plane to avoid floods and he fell in love with it.</p>
    <p>Last week, he had plas­tic pan­els in­stalled to sep­a­rate the ta­bles. The pan­els come with motifs of Ja­panese origami cranes to re­flect the flight theme.</p>
    <p>Cus­tomers are each given a Sushi Air­ways board­ing pass as a sou­venir, and the menu is de­signed like a flight man­ual. Pop­u­lar items in­clude Dou­ble Sal­mon Maki ($29+), a rice roll made with raw sal­mon and deep-fried sal­mon skin.</p>
    <p>A value-for-money choice is the Bara Chi­rashi Set ($26+), avail­able only for lunch on week­days.</p>
    <p>For In­sta­gram-wor­thy food, go for Sawa­gani ($23+), tiny fresh wa­ter­fall crabs which are deep­fried and plated on a ce­ramic tree trunk plate with peb­bles and rocks.</p>
    <p>There is also Fresh Oys­ter ($10+ for small; $15+ for medium), which comes with ponzu jelly and is dec­o­rated with fresh ed­i­ble flow­ers.</p>

